<p id="fs-id1165042512677">For the following problems, consider a lifeguard at a circular pool with diameter <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mn>40</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>m</mtext><mo>.</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mn>40</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>m</mtext><mo>.</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> He must reach someone who is drowning on the exact opposite side of the pool, at position <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>.</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>.</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> The lifeguard swims with a speed <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mi>v</mi></annotation-xml></semantics></math> and runs around the pool at speed <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>w</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>v</mi><mo>.</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>w</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>v</mi><mo>.</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math></p>
